# Keycloak Authentication

## Architecture

- **Keycloak** handles all authentication (login, registration, password reset, email verification). The app has no custom auth forms.
- Users sign up with **first name, last name, email, and password** only. There is no username — `registrationEmailAsUsername: true` in the realm config makes email the username automatically.
- The frontend uses `react-oidc-context` with OIDC Authorization Code + PKCE flow. Config lives in `frontend/src/auth/oidcConfig.ts`.
- The backend validates Keycloak JWTs. The `GET /api/auth/me` endpoint auto-provisions a `Student` record from token claims on first login.

## User Identity

- Display name is built from `given_name` + `family_name` JWT claims, never from `preferred_username`.
- Backend: `AuthController.cs` reads `given_name` and `family_name` claims.
- Frontend: `authStore.ts` reads `profile.given_name` and `profile.family_name` from the OIDC user.
- If both are empty, fall back to the `name` claim, then `"Student"`.

## Keycloak Theme (integrated in frontend)

- The theme lives at `frontend/src/keycloak-theme/` — it is part of the frontend Vite project, sharing React, styles, and hot reload.
- Built with **Keycloakify** (v11+). The Vite plugin is in `frontend/vite.config.ts`. `npm run build-keycloak-theme` in the frontend directory compiles the JAR to `frontend/dist_keycloak/`.
- `frontend/src/main.tsx` is the shared entrypoint: if `window.kcContext` exists (Keycloak is serving the page), it renders the theme; otherwise it renders the app via lazy-loaded `main.app.tsx`.
- To preview theme pages in dev mode, uncomment the mock block in `main.tsx` and run `npm run dev`.
- All user-facing text is **hardcoded in Danish** — no `msg()` or `msgStr()` calls in page components. The i18n layer (`login/i18n.ts`) overrides Keycloak message keys (e.g., `username` → `"E-mail"`) as a safety net for any server-rendered messages.
- Custom pages: `Login.tsx`, `Register.tsx`, `LoginResetPassword.tsx`, `LoginVerifyEmail.tsx`, `Info.tsx`. All other pages fall through to `DefaultPage`.
- Styles live in `login/main.css` using the `mat-*` BEM class convention and CSS variables.
- The registration form uses Keycloakify's `UserProfileFormFields` component. The username field is hidden via CSS (`.kcFormGroupClass:has(#username) { display: none }`).

## Realm Configuration (IaC)

- All realm config is in **Terraform** (`infra/keycloak.tf`). This is the single source of truth for both production (`mat-tutor`) and dev (`mat-tutor-dev`) realms.
- Managed resources: `keycloak_realm`, `keycloak_openid_client`, `keycloak_openid_audience_protocol_mapper`, `keycloak_realm_user_profile`.
- **Never** configure realms via the Keycloak Admin Console — changes will be overwritten by the next `terraform apply`.
- Key realm settings: `registration_email_as_username = true`, `default_locale = "da"`, `verify_email = true`.
- `infra/keycloak/realm-dev-export.json` still exists for local dev only (used by root `docker-compose.yml`).

## Local Dev

- `docker-compose.yml` at repo root runs Keycloak + Postgres locally on port 8080.
- `frontend/.env` points `VITE_OIDC_AUTHORITY` at `http://localhost:8080/realms/mat-tutor-dev`.
- `npm run dev:local` from repo root starts Keycloak (Docker) + frontend dev server.
- Theme changes are visible instantly via Vite hot reload when using the mock context in `main.tsx`.

## Deploy Pipeline

1. `terraform apply` in CI manages all infrastructure + Keycloak realm config.
2. Theme JAR is built in CI (`npm run build-keycloak-theme` in `frontend/`), SCPed to `/opt/keycloak/providers/`.
3. Keycloak container is restarted to pick up the new theme JAR.

## Login Form Internals

- The login `<input name="username">` field must keep `name="username"` and `id="username"` — Keycloak's server-side form handler requires this POST parameter name. The **label** says "E-mail" and `type="email"`.
